ENVS363 Computational Essay¶

Computational essays are a powerful means of learning and expressing facts and ideas (Wolfram, 2017). This computational essay explores two datasets related to the Canadian city of Toronto and is split into two parts. Part I focuses on the socioeconomic characteristics of Toronto (neis) while Part II analyses patterns of photographs taken in Toronto (photos). Additional datasets are implemented throughout both sections in order to create insights into the relationships between datasets.

Part I¶

The first task is to select two variables from the socioeconomic characteristics of Toronto dataset. From the list of variables, I have selected 'hh_median_income2015' and 'deg_bachelor'.

I have chosen the median household income and bachelor degree variables as research suggests there is a significant relationship between higher education degree attainment, employment, and earnings, with those qualified earning more than those without (Berger and Parkin, 2009-11). The second task entails exploring the spatial distribution of these variables. These variables will be spatially analysed using choropleths. Choropleths display the spatial distribution of a variable's value encoded in a colour scheme. I will convert the variable values using Equal interval data classification with 7 segments in order to make differences between boundaries clearer.

Choropleth maps for Median Income and Bachelor Degree

Both choropleths display one significant cluster featuring the highest concentration of median household income and bachelors degree. Furthermore, both choropleths display similar patterns of clustering suggesting there is a relationship between higher education attainment and median income. However, Choropleths only geovisually represent this relationship therefore, in task three Local Spatial Autocorrelation will be used to test the relationships between each observation and its surroundings. Local Indicators of Spatial Association (LISAs) are a local counter-part of Moran's I utilised in Local Spatial Autocorrelation which identifies 'hotspots' by focusing on the relationship between each observation and its surroundings (Anselin, 1995).

Spatial weights matrix formally encodes geographical space into a numerical form needed for spatial autocorrelation

In [6]:
# Create the spatial weights matrix
%time w = weights.Queen.from_dataframe(neis, idVariable="_id")

Wall time: 183 ms

Matrix is row-standardized so every row of the matrix sums up to one

In [7]:
# Row standardize the matrix
w.transform = 'R'

Average value is then subtracted and divided by the standard deviation of each observation

In [8]:
neis['deg_bachelor_std'] = (
    neis['deg_bachelor'] - neis['deg_bachelor'].mean()
) / neis['deg_bachelor'].std()
In [9]:
neis['hh_median_income2015_std'] = (
    neis['hh_median_income2015'] - neis['hh_median_income2015'].mean()
) / neis['hh_median_income2015'].std()

The spatial lag averages the neighbouring values of a location

In [10]:
neis['w_deg_bachelor_std'] = weights.lag_spatial(w, neis['deg_bachelor_std']) 
neis['w_hh_median_income2015_std'] = weights.lag_spatial(w, neis['hh_median_income2015_std'])

Degree of Spatial Autocorrelation

# Add vertical and horizontal lines

plt.text(.75, 1.5, "HH", fontsize=25)
plt.text(.75, -.75, "HL", fontsize=25)

plt.text(-.25, -.75, "LL", fontsize=25)

# Save figures
plt.savefig('Median Income and Bachelor Degree Local Spatial Autocorrelion.jpg')

LISAs classify observations into quadrants which fall into the Moran Plot. LISAs identify cases in which the comparison between the value of an observation and the average of its neighbours is either more similar (HH, LL) or dissimilar (HL, LH) than we would expect from pure chance. The output suggests that there is a positive local spatial autocorrelation between higher education attainment and median income suggesting similar values (HH, LL) of tend to be clustered together. This supports the relationship between higher education attainment and median income.

Part II¶

The second dataset (photos) is a subsample of a 100 million Yahoo dataset containing the location of photographs uploaded to the Flickr service. Using the photographs, the first task is to visualise the dataset appropriately.

The scatter plot shows that photographs tend to display a non-random pattern which is concentrated in localized clusters. Scatter plots are ideal for identfying patterns in data as they plot individal points (photos), however, as the dataset is large it is harder to identify points areas of interest (AOI) beyond that large cluster. Adding a basemap makes the pattern of photographs clearer and relates the concentrated cluster to a geography: 'Downtown Toronto'. Downtown Toronto is Canada's central business district, containing three universities and one of North America's largest clusters of skyscrapers and businesses. This explains why that one cluster in the choropleth maps contained the highest educational attainment and median income. The second task is to use DBSCAN algorithm to identify AOI with high densities of photographs. To run DBSCAN, parameters determining the minimum number of points in a cluster (min_sample) and maximum radious to search for points within a cluster (eps) must be set. I have set the parameters as 50 photographs in a 500m radius as... convert to Canadian CRS.

Before setting up the algorithm, the longitude and latitude needs to be expressed in metres and photos needs to be transformed into a GeoDataFrame

In [14]:
## Express points in metres
# Convert lon/lat into Point objects + set CRS
pts = gpd.points_from_xy(
    photos["longitude"],
    photos["latitude"],
    crs="EPSG:4326"
)
# Convert lon/lat points to Canadian CRS in metres
pts = gpd.GeoDataFrame({"geometry": pts}).to_crs(epsg=3978)
# Extract coordinates from point objects into columns
photos["X_metres"] = pts.geometry.x
photos["Y_metres"] = pts.geometry.y

Different parameters can give rise to substantially different outcomes even with the same data and algorithm. This effect is evident when utilising the interactive tool below.

In [23]:
def clusters(photos_gdf, eps, min_samples):
    '''
    Compute and visualize DBSCAN clusters    
    ...
    
    Arguments
    ---------
    db          : (Geo)DataFrame
                  Table with at least columns `X` and `Y` for point coordinates
    eps         : float
                  Maximum radious to search for points within a cluster
    min_samples : int
                  Minimum number of points in a cluster
    '''
    algo = DBSCAN(eps=eps, min_samples=min_samples)
    algo.fit(photos_gdf[['X_metres', 'Y_metres']])
    lbls = pd.Series(algo.labels_, index=photos_gdf.index)

    f, ax = plt.subplots(1, figsize=(6, 6))
    noise = photos_gdf.loc[lbls==-1, ['X_metres', 'Y_metres']]
    ax.scatter(noise['X_metres'], noise['Y_metres'], c='grey', s=5, linewidth=0)
    ax.scatter(
        photos_gdf.loc[photos_gdf.index.difference(noise.index), 'X_metres'],
        photos_gdf.loc[photos_gdf.index.difference(noise.index), 'Y_metres'],
        c='red', 
        linewidth=0
    )
    return plt.show()
In [24]:
interact(
    clusters,                 # Method to make interactive
    photos_gdf=fixed(photos),          # Data to pass on db (does not change)
    eps=(50, 500, 50),        # Range start/end/step of eps
    min_samples=(5, 300, 5) # Range start/end/step of min_samples
);
